Problem Statement: Maximum Number of Rainbows
You are given a string S consisting of lowercase English letters.
A rainbow can be formed only if the string contains all the following characters:
v i b g y o r
Each character can be used only once in forming a rainbow.

Your task is to find the maximum number of rainbows that can be formed using the characters of the given string.

Rules:

Each character in the string can be used at most once.
Characters can be used in any order.
Extra characters in the string can be ignored.
A rainbow is valid only if all 7 characters (v, i, b, g, y, o, r) are present.

Input Format:
A single line containing the string S.

Output Format:
Print a single integer representing the maximum number of rainbows that can be formed.

Constraints:

1 ≤ length of S ≤ 10⁵
S contains only lowercase English letters.

Sample Input 1:
vbgiybro

Sample Output 1:
1

Sample Input 2:
vvbggybbrro

Sample Output 2:
0

Explanation:

To form one rainbow, all characters v, i, b, g, y, o, r must be present at least once.
The maximum number of rainbows is determined by the minimum frequency of these characters in the string.

// Java Code 

import java.util.*;
pubic class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
          Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
          String S = sc.nextLine();
          int v=0, i=0, b=0, g=0, y=0, o=0, r=0;
          for(char ch : s.toCharArray()) {
               if(c == 'v')
                  v++;
               else if(c == 'i')
                   i++;
               else if(c == 'b')
                    b++;
              else if(c == 'g')
                    g++;
              else if(c == 'y')
                   y++;
              else if(c == 'o')
                    o++;
              else if(c == 'r')
                    r++;
           }
           int ans = v;
           ans = Math.min(ans, i);
           ans = Math.min(ans, b);
           ans = Math.min(ans, g);
           ans = Math.min(ans, y);
           ans = Math.min(ans, o);
           ans = Math.min(ans, r);
           System.ou.println(ans);
           sc.close();
       }
}
